[1] Utah (Sanpete County)
Date: Thu 28 Jul 2022
Source: WATT Poultry [edited]
https://www.wattagnet.com/articles/45526-avian-influenza-found-in-third-utah-turkey-flock


The presence of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) has been confirmed in another commercial turkey flock in Utah. The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) reported that on 26 Jul 2022, HPAI was confirmed in a flock of 12 700 turkeys in Sanpete County, Utah, making it the 3rd HPAI case in that county.

The 2 previous cases in Sanpete County were confirmed on 14 Jul 2022 and 19 Jul 2022 -- both of which were larger flocks than the most recently affected one. Between the 3 flocks, avian influenza has affected 38 800 commercial turkeys in Sanpete County.

The latest case marks the 4th case of HPAI in Utah in 2022. The 1st case was confirmed on 22 Apr 2022 in a commercial table egg layer flock in Cache County. There were more than 1.5 million layers in that flock.

Backyard flocks in the Utah counties of Utah, Salt Lake and Cache have also been affected by HPAI, as has a petting zoo/exhibition farm in Salt Lake County. With the exception of the 3 Sanpete County cases, the control areas related to all other HPAI cases in Utah have been released, according to APHIS.

Prior to the 3 Sanpete County cases, the last case of HPAI in the United States was confirmed on 9 Jun 2022 in a flock of 205 000 commercial layer pullets in Weld County, Colorado.

So far in 2022, HPAI has been confirmed in commercial poultry in the states of Michigan, Wisconsin, Oklahoma, Minnesota, North Dakota, South Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, Iowa, Missouri, Kentucky, Indiana, Colorado, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland and Utah. The virus has also been found in commercial game bird operations in Texas, New York and South Dakota.

[Byline: Roy Graber]

