******
[4] Washington (Walla Walla County)
Date: Tue 16 Aug 2022 11:06 PDT
Source: KIRO 7 News [edited]
https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/after-three-week-break-hiatus-bird-flu-detected-walla-walla-county/WS3VTE4SEVGX7EC3JVZRSQ4TUY/


After nearly a 3-week break in bird flu detections, avian influenza was detected in a Walla Walla County backyard flock on 12 Aug 2022, bringing the state-wide flock total to 31. Even though cases have slowed in Washington, neighboring states continue to detect bird flu, indicating the virus is still in the environment. [Migration southward will soon begin, so all bird owners need to be on the alert again. - Mod.TG]

"While we had hoped cases would [taper] off by now, current trends suggest that resident wild waterfowl are creating a reservoir of ongoing infection. We must stay vigilant and prepared to respond for the coming weeks, and potentially months," Washington State veterinarian Dr. Amber Itle said.

Flock owners within 10 kilometers (6.2 mi) of a detection are encouraged to self-report the health of their flock via the WSDA online surveillance self-reporting tool.

Itle says the biggest risk factor is direct contact with wild waterfowl. All 31 infected flocks have had contact with them.

Flock owners should be discouraged to bring their birds to fairs, exhibitions, poultry auctions, and on-farm sales until there hasn't been a detection in the state for 30 days. If your flock experiences sudden death or illness of several birds, call the WSDA Sick Bird Hotline.

[Byline: Shawn Garrett]

